<subSubSection lastPageId="49" lastPageNumber="50" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="47.[189,1399,1930,2027]" lastBlockId="49.[189,1399,267,366]" lastPageId="49" lastPageNumber="50" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
For a very long time, up to the early 1960s and 1970s, 
<taxonomicName box="[868,1016,1930,1956]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Nanonycteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aethiopia">
<emphasis box="[868,1016,1930,1956]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">N. aethiopia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been considered a separate species (from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dobson" authorityYear="1876" box="[364,504,1966,1991]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Nanonycteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrotis">
<emphasis box="[364,504,1966,1991]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">N. macrotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Hayman" box="[532,838,1965,1992]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Hayman" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="1 - 105" refId="ref265860" refString="Hayman R. W., Misonne X. &amp; Verheyen W. N. 1966. The bats of the Congo and of Rwanda and Burundi. Annalen van het Koninklijk Museum voor Midden Afrika, Zoologische Wetenschappen, Ser. 8, 154: 1 - 105." type="journal article" year="1966">
Hayman 
<emphasis box="[643,706,1965,1991]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">et al.</emphasis>
(1966: 33
</bibRefCitation>
, 35, 36) followed that view, but also referred to Koopman, who indicated that 
<emphasis box="[585,709,2001,2027]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">aethiopica</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dobson" authorityYear="1876" box="[771,873,2002,2027]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Nanonycteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrotis">
<emphasis box="[771,873,2002,2027]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">macrotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are conspecific. 
<bibRefCitation author="Hayman &amp; Hill" box="[1076,1398,2001,2027]" firstAuthor="Hayman" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" refId="ref265812" refString="Hayman R. W. &amp; Hill J. E. 1971. Order Chiroptera. In: Meester J. &amp; Setzer H. W. (eds) The Mammals of Africa, an Identification Manual. Part 2. Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington." type="book" year="1971">Hayman &amp; Hill (1971: 19)</bibRefCitation>
still mention the two as separate species, but note that their distinctness is by no means clear, as was suggested by 
<bibRefCitation author="Koopman" box="[356,561,303,330]" firstAuthor="Koopman" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" pagination="1 - 34" refId="ref268567" refString="Koopman K. F. 1965. Status of forms described or recorded by J. A. Allen in the &quot; American Museum Congo Expedition of Bats &quot;. American Museum Novitates 2219: 1 - 34. Available from http: // hdl. handle. net / 2246 / 4012 [accessed 29 Nov. 2017]." type="journal article" year="1965">Koopman (1965)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Kock" box="[625,781,303,330]" firstAuthor="Kock" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" pagination="1 - 238" refId="ref268151" refString="Kock D. 1969. Die Fledermaus-Fauna des Sudan (Mammalia, Chiroptera). Abhandlungen der Senckenbergischen naturforschenden Gesellschaft 521: 1 - 238." type="journal article" year="1969">Kock (1969)</bibRefCitation>
. The multivariate analyses by 
<bibRefCitation author="Van Cakenberghe &amp; De Vree" firstAuthor="Van Cakenberghe" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" pagination="53 - 90" refId="ref274582" refString="Van Cakenberghe V. &amp; De Vree F. 1985. Systematics of African Nycteris (Mammalia: Chiroptera). Proceedings of the International Symposium on African Vertebrates, Bonn: 53 - 90." type="proceedings paper" year="1985">Van Cakenberghe &amp; De Vree (1985)</bibRefCitation>
confirmed that the two forms are conspecific.
</paragraph>
